SIMPLE: mug
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mug
<hw>Mug</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Ir.
<ets>mugam</ets> a mug, <ets>mucog</ets> a cup.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A kind of ceramic or metal drinking cup, with a handle, -- usually
cylindrical and without a lip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The face or mouth; <as>as, I don't want to see your
ugly <ex>mug</ex> again</as>; -- often used contemptuously.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: mug
<hw>mug</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To take property
from (a person) in a public place by threatening or committing violence
on the person who is robbed; to rob, especially to rob by use of a
weapon such as a knife or gun.</def> <note>To rob a person or a business
indoors is not usually referred to as to <ex>mug</ex>, but to
<contr>stick up</contr> or <contr>hold up</contr>.</note>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rob, stick up</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mugful</ent>⟦br⟧
